# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fuel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] Historically, 1,2-dibromoethane was used as a component in anti-knock additives in leaded fuels.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] It reacts with lead residues to generate volatile lead bromides, thereby preventing fouling of the engine with lead deposits.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] It has been used as a pesticide in soil and on various crops.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] The applications were initiated after the forced retirement of 1,2-dibromo-3-chloropropane (DBCP).
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] Most of these uses have been stopped in the U.S.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] It continues to be used as a fumigant for treatment of logs for termites and beetles, and for control of moths in beehives.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] 1,2-Dibromoethane has wider applications in the preparation of other organic compounds including those carrying modified diazocine rings and vinyl bromide that is a precursor to some fire retardants.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] In organic synthesis, 1,2-dibromoethane is used to brominate carbanions and to activate magnesium for certain Grignard reagents.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] In the latter process, 1,2-dibromoethane reacts with magnesium, producing ethylene and magnesium bromide, which are innocuous, exposing a more active portion of the magnesium particle to the substrate.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] 1,2-Dibromoethane causes changes in the metabolism and severe destruction of living tissues.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] The known empirical LD50 values for 1,2-dibromoethane are 140 mg kg−1 (oral, rat), and 300.0 mg kg−1 (dermal, rabbit).
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] 1,2-Dibromoethane is a known carcinogen, with pre-1977 exposure levels ranking it as the most carcinogenic substance on the HERP Index.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] The effects on people of breathing high levels are not known, but animal studies with short-term exposures to high levels caused depression and collapse, indicating effects on the brain.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] Changes in the brain and behavior were also seen in young rats whose male parents had breathed 1,2-dibromoethane, and birth defects were observed in the young of animals that were exposed while pregnant.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] 1,2-Dibromoethane is not known to cause birth defects in humans.
[src:fuel/1-2-dibromoethane] Swallowing has caused death at 40ml doses.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] The chemical compound **1,2-dichloroethane**, commonly known as **ethylene dichloride** (**EDC**), is a chlorinated hydrocarbon.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] It is a colourless liquid with a chloroform-like odour.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] The most common use of 1,2-dichloroethane is in the production of vinyl chloride, which is used to make polyvinyl chloride (PVC) pipes, furniture and automobile upholstery, wall coverings, housewares, and automobile parts.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] 1,2-Dichloroethane is also used generally as an intermediate for other organic chemical compounds, and as a solvent.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] It forms azeotropes with many other solvents, including water (at a boiling point of 70.5 °C or 158.9 °F or 343.6 K) and other chlorocarbons.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] Although the *Gezelschap* in practice did not do much in-depth scientific research, they and their publications were highly regarded.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] Part of that acknowledgement is that 1,2-dichloroethane was called "Dutch oil" in old chemistry.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] This is also the origin of the archaic term "olefiant gas" (oil-making gas) for ethylene, for in this reaction it is ethylene that makes the Dutch oil.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] "Olefiant gas" is the etymological origin of the modern term "olefins", the family of hydrocarbons of which ethylene is the first member.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] Nearly 20 million tons of 1,2-dichloroethane are produced annually in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] Approximately 95% of the world's production of 1,2-dichloroethane is used in the production of vinyl chloride monomer (VCM) with hydrogen chloride as a byproduct.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] VCM is the precursor to polyvinyl chloride.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] The hydrogen chloride can be re-used in the production of more 1,2-dichloroethane via the oxychlorination route described above.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] 1,2-Dichloroethane has been used as degreaser and paint remover but this use has phased out due to its toxicity.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] As a useful 'building block' reagent, it is used as an intermediate in the production of diverse organic compounds such as ethylenediamine and higher ethyleneamines.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] In the laboratory it is occasionally used as a source of chlorine, with elimination of ethene and chloride.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] Via several steps, 1,2-dichloroethane is a precursor to 1,1,1-trichloroethane.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] Historically, before leaded petrol was phased out, chloroethanes were used as an additive in petrol to prevent lead buildup in engines.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] It is also toxic (especially by inhalation due to its high vapour pressure) and possibly carcinogenic.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] Its high solubility and 50-year half-life in anoxic aquifers make it a perennial pollutant and health risk that is very expensive to treat conventionally, requiring a method of bioremediation.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] While the chemical is not used in consumer products manufactured in the U.S., a case was reported in 2009 of molded plastic consumer products (toys and holiday decorations) from China that released 1,2-dichloroethane into homes at levels high enough to produce cancer risk.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] Substitutes are recommended and will vary according to application.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] Dioxolane and toluene are possible substitutes as solvents.
[src:fuel/1-2-dichloroethane] Dichloroethane is unstable in the presence of aluminium and, when moist, with zinc and iron.
[src:fuel/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] It is used as an antioxidant, e.g. to prevent gumming in fuels, and as an ultraviolet stabilizer.
[src:fuel/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] It is used in jet fuels, gasolines, and avgas.
[src:fuel/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] It is prepared by alkylation of xylenol with isobutylene.
[src:fuel/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] This alkylation provides a means to separate 2,4-xylenol from 2,5-xylenol since 2,4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol is insoluble in 10% NaOH but 2,5-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol is soluble.
[src:fuel/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] Subsequent to separation, the tert-butyl group can be removed in strong acid.
[src:fuel/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] One of its trade names is **Topanol A**.
[src:fuel/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] It is found in antioxidant mixtures AO-30, AO-31, AO-32, IONOL K72, IONOL K78, IONOL K98, and others.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] In this way, approximately 2.5M kg/y are produced.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] Alkylation of phenol usually favours the para-position, and a strong lewis acid such as the Al3+ ion is necessary to give selective ortho‑alkylation.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] If a conventional brønsted acid is used then 2,4-di-tert-butylphenol will be produced instead.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] Two species of plants, *Jastropa curcas* and *Metaplexis japonica*, contain 2,6-DTBP in seeds.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] 2,6-Di-tert-butylphenol is used in the synthesis of 4,4′-biphenol.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] The process involves oxidative coupling of followed by removal of the tert-butyl groups.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] 2,6-di-*tert*-butylphenol is a precursor to antioxidants and light-protection agents for the stabilization for polymers.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] One such case is methyl-3-(3,5-di-*tert*-butyl-4-hydroxyphenyl)-propionate (CAS# 6386-38-5), which is formed by the Michael addition of methyl acrylate.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] This compound is used in the synthesis of more complex antioxidants such as Irganox 1098.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] 2,6-Di-*tert*-butylphenol is also used in the synthesis of CGP-7930, probucol, and nicanartine.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] The LD50 is 9200 mg/kg, indicating a low toxicity.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] 2,6-Di-tert-butylphenol is covered by the U.S.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] Department of Transportation Code of Federal Regulations 49 CFR 172.101, Appendix B (20 Dec 2004).
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] This substance is designated by the U.S.
[src:fuel/2-6-di-tert-butylphenol] Department of Transportation (DOT) as a marine pollutant.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Apart from what al-Mas'udi writes of himself little is known.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Born in Baghdad, he was descended from Abdullah ibn Mas'ud, a companion of Islamic prophet Muhammad.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] It is believed that he was a member of Banu Hudhayl tribe of Arabs.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Masʿudi may have reached Sri Lanka and China although he is known to have met Abu Zayd al-Sirafi on the coast of the Persian Gulf and received information on China from him.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He presumably gathered information on Byzantium from the Byzantine admiral, Leo of Tripoli, a convert-to-Islam whom he met in Syria where his last years were divided between there and Egypt.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] In Egypt he found a copy of a Frankish king list from Clovis to Louis IV that had been written by an Andalusian bishop.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Little is known of his means and funding of his extensive travels within and beyond the lands of Islam, and it has been speculated that like many travelers he was involved in trade.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] We know that al-Masʿudi wrote a revised edition of *Murūj al-Dhahab* in 956 CE; however, only a draft version from 947 is extant.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Masʿudi in his *Tanbīh* states that the revised edition of *Murūj al-Dhahab* contained 365 chapters.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Masʿudi lived at a time when books were available and cheap.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Major cities like Baghdad had large public libraries and many individuals, such as as-Suli, a friend of al-Mas‘udi's, had private libraries, often containing thousands of volumes.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Early in the Abbasid era the art of papermaking was brought to the Islamic world by Chinese prisoners after the battle of Talas and most large towns and cities had paper mills.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Available cheap writing material contributed to the lively intellectual life.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Mas'udi often refers readers to his other books, assuming their availability.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] The high literacy and vigor of the Islamic world with its rich cultural heritage of Greek philosophy, Persian literature, Indian mathematics, contrasted with that of Europe, when the author of the *Anglo-Saxon Chronicle* was writing.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Islamic Abbasid society of al-Masʿudi's world manifested a knowledge seeking, perceptive analytical attitude and scholarly-minded people associated naturally in this highly civilized atmosphere.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Mas'udi was a pupil, or junior colleague, of prominent intellectuals, including the philologists al-Zajjaj, Ibn Duraid, Niftawayh and ibn Anbari.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He was acquainted with famous poets, including Kashajim, whom he probably met in Aleppo.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He was well read in philosophy, the works of al-Kindi and al-Razi, the Aristotelian thought of al-Farabi and the Platonic writings.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] It is probable that al-Masʿudi met al-Razi and al-Farabi, but only a meeting with al-Farabi's pupil Yahya ibn Adi, of whom he spoke highly, is recorded.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He was familiar with the medical work of Galen, with Ptolemaic astronomy, with the geographical work of Marinus and with the studies of Islamic geographers and astronomers.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He mentions meeting influential jurists and cites the work of others and indicates training in jurisprudence.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] According to al-Subki, al-Mas'udi was a student of Ibn Surayj, the leading scholar of the Shafi'ite school.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Subki claimed he found al-Mas'udi's notes of Ibn Surayj's lectures.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Mas'udi also met Shafi'ites during his stay in Egypt.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He met Zahirites in Baghdad and Aleppo such as Ibn Jabir and Niftawayh; modern scholarship leans toward the view that al-Mas'udi was an adherent of the latter school.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Masʿudi knew leading Mu'tazilites, including al-Jubba, al-Nawbakhti, Ibn Abdak al-Jurjani and Abu'l-Qasim al-Balkhi al-Ka'bi.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He was also well acquainted with previous Mu'tazilite literature.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] His reasoning, his phraseology, and his expressed high esteem for Mu'tazilities could suggest that he was one of their number.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] However, Shboul points out that his extant works do not specifically state that he was.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Mas'udi included the history of the ancient civilizations that had occupied the land upon which Islam later spread.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He mentions the Assyrians, Babylonians, Egyptians and Persians among others.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He is also the only Arab historian to refer (albeit indirectly) to the kingdom of Urartu, when he speaks about the wars between the Assyrians (led by the legendary Queen Semiramis) and Armenians (led by King Ara the Handsome).
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Masʿudi was aware of the influence of ancient Babylon on Persia.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He had access to a wealth of translations by scholars such as Abdullah ibn al-Muqaffa from Middle Persian into Arabic.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] In his travels, he also personally consulted Persian scholars and Zoroastrian priests.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He thus had access to much material, factual and mythical.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Like other Arabic historians, he was unclear on the Achaemenid dynasty, though he knew of Kurush (Cyrus the Great).
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He was much clearer on the more recent dynasties and his estimation of the time between Alexander the Great and Ardashir is much more accurately depicted than it is in al-Tabari.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] His wide-ranging interests included the Greeks and the Romans.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Again, like other Arabic historians, he was unclear on Greece before the Macedonian dynasty that produced Alexander the Great.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He is aware that there were kings before this, but is unclear on their names and reigns.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He also seems unfamiliar with such additional aspects of Greek political life as Athenian democratic institutions.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] The same holds for Rome prior to Caesar.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] However, he is the earliest extant Arabic author to mention the Roman founding myth of Romulus and Remus.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] In al-Masʿudi's view the greatest contribution of the Greeks was philosophy.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He was aware of the progression of Greek philosophy from the pre-Socratics onward.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He also was keenly interested in the earlier events of the Arabian peninsula.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He recognized that Arabia had a long and rich history.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Ahmad Shboul notes that al-Mas'udi is distinguished above his contemporaries for the extent of his interest in and coverage of the non-Islamic lands and peoples of his day.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Other authors, even Christians writing in Arabic in the Caliphate, had less to say about the Byzantine Empire than al-Mas'udi.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He also described the geography of many lands beyond the Abbasid Caliphate, as well as the customs and religious beliefs of many peoples.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] His normal inquiries of travelers and extensive reading of previous writers were supplemented in the case of India with his personal experiences in the western part of the subcontinent.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He demonstrates a deep understanding of historical change, tracing current conditions to the unfolding of events over generations and centuries.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He perceived the significance of interstate relations and of the interaction of Muslims and Hindus in the various states of the subcontinent.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He described previous rulers in China, underlined the importance of the revolt by Huang Chao in the late Tang dynasty, and mentioned, though less detailed than for India, Chinese beliefs.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] His brief portrayal of Southeast Asia stands out for its degree of accuracy and clarity.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He surveyed the vast areas inhabited by Turkic peoples, commenting on what had been the extensive authority of the Khaqan, though this was no longer the case by al-Mas'udi's time.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He conveyed the great diversity of Turkic peoples, including the distinction between sedentary and nomadic Turks.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He spoke of the significance of the Khazars and provided much fresh material on them.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] His account of the Rus is an important early source for the study of Russian history and the history of Ukraine.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Again, while he may have read such earlier Arabic authors as Ibn Khordadbeh, Ibn al-Faqih, ibn Rustah and Ibn Fadlan, al-Mas'udi presented most of his material based on his personal observations and contacts made while traveling.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He informed the Arabic reader that the Rus were more than just a few traders.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] They were a diverse and varied collection of peoples.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He noted their independent attitude, the absence of a strong central authority among them and their paganism.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He was very well informed on Rus trade with the Byzantines and on the competence of the Rus in sailing merchant vessels and warships.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He was aware that the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea are two separate bodies of water.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Masʿudi was also very well informed about Byzantine affairs, even internal political events and the unfolding of palace coups.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He recorded the effect of the westward migration of various tribes upon the Byzantines, especially the invading Bulgars.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He spoke of Byzantine relations with western Europe.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] And, of course, he was attentively interested in Byzantine-Islamic relations.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] One example of al-Masʿudi's influence on Muslim knowledge of the Byzantine world is that the use of the name Istanbul (in place of Constantinople) can be traced to his writings during the year 947, centuries before the eventual Ottoman use of this term.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He writes that the Greeks (i.e. the Byzantines of the tenth century) call it "the City" (*bulin* in the Arabic script, which lacks the letter p: so Greek *polin*); "and when they wish to express that it is the capital of the Empire because of its greatness they say Istan Bulin.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He has some knowledge of other peoples of eastern and western Europe, even far away Britain and Anglo-Saxon England.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He names it, though he is sketchy about it.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He obtained a copy of a list of Frankish rulers from Clovis to his own time.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He makes several references to people interpreted as Vikings, described by him as Majus, they came to Al-Andalus from the North.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Masʿudi's global interest included Africa.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He was well aware of peoples in the eastern portion of the continent (mentioning interesting details of the Zanj, for example).
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He mentioned that one of the most dangerous routes to travel is to the land of the Zanj, "I have sailed on many seas, but I do not know of one more dangerous than that of Zanj", also saying that several captains that he had sailed with drowned.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He knows less of West Africa, though he names such contemporary states as Zagawa, Kawkaw and Ghana.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He described the relations of African states with each other and with Islam.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He provided material on the cultures and beliefs of non-Islamic Africans.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Lunde and Stone have provided the English reader with a fluent translation of some three-quarters of al-Masʿudi's material on the Abbasids from the *Murūj al-dhahab*.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] This is in the form of more than two hundred passages, many of these containing amusing and informative anecdotes.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] The very first one recounts the meeting of al-Mansur and a blind poet unaware of the identity of his distinguished interlocutor.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] The poet on two separate occasions recites praise poems for the defeated Umayyads to the Abbasid caliph; al-Mansur good naturedly rewards him.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] 28 ff.) of the arrow that landed at al-Mansur's feet with verses inscribed in each of the three feathers and along the shaft causing him to investigate the unjust imprisonment of a distinguished notable from Hamadan.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] There is the story of the singer Harun al-Rashid asks to keep singing until the caliph falls asleep.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Then a handsome young man arrives, snatches the lute from the singer's hand and shows him how it really should be done.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] On awakening Harun is told of this and suggests his singer had a supernatural visitation.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Al-Mas'udi quotes the lines (five in English) of this remarkable song.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] These anecdotes provide glimpses of other aspects of these prominent people, sharing, actually, greater realization of their humanity and the human concerns of their officials and ordinary subjects.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] One of the more interesting passages is the account of the symposium held at the home of Harun al-Rashid's famous vizier Yahya the Barmakid on the topic of love.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] A dozen leading thinkers provide their definition of love and then a thirteenth, a Magian judge, speaks at greater length on that theme.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Ernest Renan compared al-Masʿudi to the second century A.D.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Greek geographer Pausanias, while others compared him to the Roman writer Pliny the Elder.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] Some early commentators on al-Masudi indicate the influence of religious antagonisms.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] The Sunni scholar Ibn Hajar wrote: "[al-Mas'udi's] books are imprecise because he was a Shi‘a, a Muʿtazili." Adh-Dhahabi believed he espoused heretical Mu'tazili doctrine.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] However, according to al-Subki al-Mas'udi was a student of Ibn Surayj, the leading scholar of the Shafi'ite school.
[src:fuel/abu-al-hasan-alī-al-mas-ūdī] He also met Zahirites in Baghdad and Aleppo such as Ibn Jabir and Niftawayh; modern scholarship leans toward the view that al-Mas'udi was an adherent of the latter school.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:fuel/air-fuel-ratio] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] The term high-altitude wind power (HAWP) has been used to refer to AWE systems.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] However, semantically HAWP might also include wind energy conversion systems that are somehow positioned at a large height from the ground or sea surface.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Various mechanisms are proposed for capturing the kinetic energy of winds such as kites, kytoons, aerostats, gliders, gliders with turbines for regenerative soaring, sailplanes with turbines, or other airfoils, including multiple-point building- or terrain-enabled holdings.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Once the mechanical energy is derived from the wind's kinetic energy, then many options are available for using that mechanical energy: direct traction, conversion to electricity aloft or at ground station, conversion to laser or microwave for power beaming to other aircraft or ground receivers.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Winds at higher altitudes become steadier, more persistent, and of higher velocity.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Because power available in wind increases as the cube of velocity (the velocity-cubed law), assuming other parameters remaining the same, doubling a wind's velocity gives 23=8 times the power; tripling the velocity gives 33=27 times the available power.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] With steadier and more predictable winds, high-altitude wind has an advantage over wind near the ground.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Being able to locate HAWP to effective altitudes and using the vertical dimension of airspace for wind farming brings further advantage using high-altitude winds for generating energy.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] High-altitude wind generators can be adjusted in height and position to maximize energy return, which is impractical with fixed tower-mounted wind generators.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] In each range of altitudes there are altitude-specific concerns being addressed by researchers and developers.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] As altitude increases, tethers increase in length, the temperature of the air changes, and vulnerability to atmospheric lightning changes.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] With increasing altitude, exposure to liabilities increase, costs increase, turbulence exposure changes, likelihood of having the system fly in more than one directional strata of winds increases, and the costs of operation changes.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] HAWP systems that are flown must climb through all intermediate altitudes up to final working altitudes—being at first a low- and then a high- altitude device.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] An atlas of the high-altitude wind power resource has been prepared for all points on Earth.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] A similar atlas of global assessment was developed at Joby Energy.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] When a scheme's purpose is to propel ships and boats, the objects tether-placed in the wind will tend to have most of the captured energy be in useful tension in the main tether.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] The aloft working bodies will be operated to maintain useful tension even while the ship is moving.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] This is the method for powerkiting sports.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] This sector of HAWP is the most installed method.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Folklore suggests that Benjamin Franklin used the traction method of HAWP.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] George Pocock was a pioneer in tugging vehicles by traction.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Solutions in built systems have control mechanisms variously situated.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Some systems are passive, or active, or a mix.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] When a kite steering unit (KSU) is lofted, the KSU may be robotic and self-contained; a KSU may be operated from the ground via radio-control by a live human operator or by smart computer programs.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Some systems have built sensors in the aircraft body that report parameters like position, relative position to other parts.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Kite control units (KCU) have involved more than steering; tether reeling speeds and directions can be adjusted in response to tether tensions and needs of the system during a power-generating phase or return-non-power-generating phase.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] The mechanical energy of the device may be converted to heat, sound, electricity, light, tension, pushes, pulls, laser, microwave, chemical changes, or compression of gases.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Traction is a big direct use of the mechanical energy as in tugging cargo ships and kiteboarders.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] There are several methods of getting the mechanical energy from the wind's kinetic energy.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Lighter-than-air (LTA) moored aerostats are employed as lifters of turbines.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Heavier-than-air (HTA) tethered airfoils are being used as lifters or turbines themselves.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Combinations of LTA and HTA devices in one system are being built and flown to capture HAWP.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Even a family of free-flight airborne devices are represented in the literature that capture the kinetic energy of high-altitude winds (beginning with a description in 1967 by Richard Miller in his book *Without Visible Means of Support*) and a contemporary patent application by Dale C.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Kramer, soaring sailplane competitor, inventor.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] A research on airborne wind turbine technology innovations reveals that the “Kite type AWTs” technique, the most common type, has high scope of growth in the future; it has contributed for about 44% of the total airborne wind energy during 2008–2012.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] The kite type AWTs extract energy through wind turbines suspended at high altitudes using kites such as multi-tethered kite, kite and dual purpose circular fan, rotary wing kites etc.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Electricity generation is just one of the options for capturing mechanical energy; however, this option dominates the focus of professionals aiming to supply large amounts of energy to commerce and utilities.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] A long array of secondary options include tugging water turbines, pumping of water, or compressing air or hydrogen.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] The position of the electric generator is a distinguishing feature among systems.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Flying the generator aloft is done in a variety of ways.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Keeping the generator at the mooring region is another large design option.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] The option in one system of a generator aloft and at the ground station has been used where a small generator operates electronic devices aloft while the ground generator is the big worker to make electricity for significant loads.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] The “Carousel” configuration several kites fly at a constant height and higher altitudes, pulling in rotation a generator that moves on a wide circular rail.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] For a large Carousel system, the power obtained can be calculated as of the order of GW, exposing a law that see the power attainable as a function of the diameter raised to the fifth power, while the increment of cost of the generator is linear.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] One method of keeping working HAWP systems aloft is to use buoyant aerostats whether or not the electric generator is lifted or left on the ground.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] The aerostats are usually, but not always, shaped to achieve a kiting lifting effect.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Recharging leaked lifting gas receives various solutions.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] In case of productive winds the aerostats are typically blown down by the aerodynamic drag applied on the wide and unavoidable Reynolds surface excluding them de facto from the HAWP category.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Conceptually, two adjacent mountains (natural or terrain-enabled) or artificial buildings or towers (urban or artificial) could have a wind turbine suspended between them by use of cables.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] When HAWP is cabled between two mountain tops across a valley, the HAWP device is not airborne, but borne up by the cable system.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] No such systems are known to be in use, though patents teach these methods.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] When non-cabled bridges are the foundation for holding wind turbines high above the ground, then these are grouped with conventional towered turbines and are outside the intent of HAWP where the tethering an airborne system is foundational.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Lightning, aircraft traffic, emergency procedures, system inspections, visibility marking of system parts and its tethers, electrical safety, runaway-wing procedures, over-powering controls, appropriate mooring, and more form the safety environment for HAWP systems.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] There have been several periods of high interest in HAWP before the contemporary activity.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] The first period had a high focus on pulling carriages over the lands and capturing atmospheric electricity and lightning for human use.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] The second period was in the 1970s and 1980s when research and investment flourished; a drop in oil price resulted in no significant installations of HAWP.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Return on investment (ROI) has been the key parameter; that ROI remains in focus in the current development activity while in the background is the renewable and sustainable energy movement supporting wind power of any kind; but HAWP must compete on ROI with conventional towered solutions.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] A test center at Lista, Norway provides independent verification of research.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Early centuries of kiting demonstrated that the kite is a rotary engine that rotates its tether part about its mooring point and causes hands and arms to move because of the energy captured from higher winds into the mechanical device.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] The tension in the lofted devices performs the work of lifting and pulling body parts and things.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Airborne wind energy (AWE) for HAWP was birthed thousands of years ago; naming what happened and developing the implied potentials of tethered aircraft for doing special works is what is occurring in AWE HAWP.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] What is "low" for some workers is "high" for others.
[src:fuel/airborne-wind-energy] Autorotation is the basis of a large sector of AWE technology.
[src:fuel/fuel] The heat energy released by reactions of fuels can be converted into mechanical energy via a heat engine.
[src:fuel/fuel] Other times, the heat itself is valued for warmth, cooking, or industrial processes, as well as the illumination that accompanies combustion.
[src:fuel/fuel] Fuels are also used in the cells of organisms in a process known as cellular respiration, where organic molecules are oxidized to release usable energy.
[src:fuel/fuel] Hydrocarbons and related organic molecules are by far the most common source of fuel used by humans, but other substances, including radioactive metals, are also utilized.
[src:fuel/fuel] Fuels are contrasted with other substances or devices storing potential energy, such as those that directly release electrical energy (such as batteries and capacitors) or mechanical energy (such as flywheels, springs, compressed air, or water in a reservoir).
[src:fuel/fuel] The first known use of fuel was the combustion of firewood by *Homo erectus* nearly two million years ago.
[src:fuel/fuel] Throughout most of human history only fuels derived from plants or animal fat were used by humans.
[src:fuel/fuel] Charcoal, a wood derivative, has been used since at least 6,000 BCE for melting metals.
[src:fuel/fuel] It was only supplanted by coke, derived from coal, as European forests started to become depleted around the 18th century.
[src:fuel/fuel] Charcoal briquettes are now commonly used as a fuel for barbecue cooking.
[src:fuel/fuel] Crude oil was distilled by Persian chemists, with clear descriptions given in Arabic handbooks such as those of Muhammad ibn Zakarīya Rāzi.
[src:fuel/fuel] He described the process of distilling crude oil/petroleum into kerosene, as well as other hydrocarbon compounds, in his *Kitab al-Asrar* (*Book of Secrets*).
[src:fuel/fuel] Kerosene was also produced during the same period from oil shale and bitumen by heating the rock to extract the oil, which was then distilled.
[src:fuel/fuel] Rāzi also gave the first description of a kerosene lamp using crude mineral oil, referring to it as the "naffatah".
[src:fuel/fuel] The streets of Baghdad were paved with tar, derived from petroleum that became accessible from natural fields in the region.
[src:fuel/fuel] In the 9th century, oil fields were exploited in the area around modern Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:fuel/fuel] These fields were described by the Arab geographer Abu al-Hasan 'Alī al-Mas'ūdī in the 10th century, and by Marco Polo in the 13th century, who described the output of those wells as hundreds of shiploads.
[src:fuel/fuel] With the development of the steam engine in the United Kingdom in 1769, coal came into more common use, the combustion of which releases chemical energy that can be used to turn water into steam.
[src:fuel/fuel] Coal was later used to drive ships and locomotives.
[src:fuel/fuel] By the 19th century, gas extracted from coal was being used for street lighting in London.
[src:fuel/fuel] In the 20th and 21st centuries, the primary use of coal is to generate electricity, providing 40% of the world's electrical power supply in 2005.
[src:fuel/fuel] Fossil fuels were rapidly adopted during the Industrial Revolution, because they were more concentrated and flexible than traditional energy sources, such as water power.
[src:fuel/fuel] They have become a pivotal part of our contemporary society, with most countries in the world burning fossil fuels in order to produce power, but are falling out of favor due to the global warming and related effects that are caused by burning them.
[src:fuel/fuel] Currently the trend has been towards renewable fuels, such as biofuels like alcohols.
[src:fuel/fuel] Chemical fuels are substances that release energy by reacting with substances around them, most notably by the process of combustion.
[src:fuel/fuel] First, by their physical properties, as a solid, liquid or gas.
[src:fuel/fuel] Secondly, on the basis of their occurrence: *primary (natural fuel)* and *secondary (artificial fuel)*.
[src:fuel/fuel] Solid fuel refers to various types of solid material that are used as fuel to produce energy and provide heating, usually released through combustion.
[src:fuel/fuel] Solid fuels include wood, charcoal, peat, coal, hexamine fuel tablets, and pellets made from wood (see wood pellets), corn, wheat, rye and other grains.
[src:fuel/fuel] Solid-fuel rocket technology also uses solid fuel (see solid propellants).
[src:fuel/fuel] Solid fuels have been used by humanity for many years to create fire.
[src:fuel/fuel] Coal was the fuel source which enabled the Industrial Revolution, from firing furnaces, to running steam engines.
[src:fuel/fuel] Wood was also extensively used to run steam locomotives.
[src:fuel/fuel] Both peat and coal are still used in electricity generation today.
[src:fuel/fuel] The use of some solid fuels (e.g. coal) is restricted or prohibited in some urban areas, due to unsafe levels of toxic emissions.
[src:fuel/fuel] The use of other solid fuels as wood is decreasing as heating technology and the availability of good quality fuel improves.
[src:fuel/fuel] In some areas, smokeless coal is often the only solid fuel used.
[src:fuel/fuel] In Ireland, peat briquettes are used as smokeless fuel.
[src:fuel/fuel] They are also used to start a coal fire.
[src:fuel/fuel] Liquid fuels are combustible or energy-generating molecules that can be harnessed to create mechanical energy, usually producing kinetic energy.
[src:fuel/fuel] They must also take the shape of their container; the fumes of liquid fuels are flammable, not the fluids.
[src:fuel/fuel] Most liquid fuels in widespread use are derived from the fossilized remains of dead plants and animals by exposure to heat and pressure inside the Earth's crust.
[src:fuel/fuel] However, there are several types, such as hydrogen fuel (for automotive uses), ethanol, jet fuel and bio-diesel, which are all categorized as liquid fuels.
[src:fuel/fuel] Emulsified fuels of oil in water, such as orimulsion, have been developed as a way to make heavy oil fractions usable as liquid fuels.
[src:fuel/fuel] Many liquid fuels play a primary role in transportation and the economy.
[src:fuel/fuel] Some common properties of liquid fuels are that they are easy to transport and can be handled easily.
[src:fuel/fuel] They are also relatively easy to use for all engineering applications and in home use.
[src:fuel/fuel] Fuels like kerosene are rationed in some countries, for example in government-subsidized shops in India for home use.
[src:fuel/fuel] Conventional diesel is similar to gasoline in that it is a mixture of aliphatic hydrocarbons extracted from petroleum.
[src:fuel/fuel] Kerosene is used in kerosene lamps and as a fuel for cooking, heating, and small engines.
[src:fuel/fuel] Natural gas, composed chiefly of methane, can only exist as a liquid at very low temperatures (regardless of pressure), which limits its direct use as a liquid fuel in most applications.
[src:fuel/fuel] LP gas is a mixture of propane and butane, both of which are easily compressible gases under standard atmospheric conditions.
[src:fuel/fuel] It offers many of the advantages of compressed natural gas (CNG) but is denser than air, does not burn as cleanly, and is much more easily compressed.
[src:fuel/fuel] Commonly used for cooking and space heating, LP gas and compressed propane are seeing increased use in motorized vehicles.
[src:fuel/fuel] Propane is the third most commonly used motor fuel globally.
[src:fuel/fuel] Fuel gas is any one of a number of fuels that are gaseous under ordinary conditions.
[src:fuel/fuel] Many fuel gases are composed of hydrocarbons (such as methane or propane), hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or mixtures thereof.
[src:fuel/fuel] Such gases are sources of potential heat energy or light energy that can be readily transmitted and distributed through pipes from the point of origin directly to the place of consumption.
[src:fuel/fuel] Fuel gas is contrasted with liquid fuels and from solid fuels, though some fuel gases are liquefied for storage or transport.
[src:fuel/fuel] While their gaseous nature can be advantageous, avoiding the difficulty of transporting solid fuel and the dangers of spillage inherent in liquid fuels, it can also be dangerous.
[src:fuel/fuel] It is possible for a fuel gas to be undetected and collect in certain areas, leading to the risk of a gas explosion.
[src:fuel/fuel] For this reason, odorizers are added to most fuel gases so that they may be detected by a distinct smell.
[src:fuel/fuel] The most common type of fuel gas in current use is natural gas.
[src:fuel/fuel] Biofuel can be broadly defined as solid, liquid, or gas fuel consisting of, or derived from biomass.
[src:fuel/fuel] Biomass can also be used directly for heating or power—known as *biomass fuel*.
[src:fuel/fuel] Biofuel can be produced from any carbon source that can be replenished rapidly e.g. plants.
[src:fuel/fuel] Many different plants and plant-derived materials are used for biofuel manufacture.
[src:fuel/fuel] Perhaps the earliest fuel employed by humans is wood.
[src:fuel/fuel] Evidence shows controlled fire was used up to 1.5 million years ago at Swartkrans, South Africa.
[src:fuel/fuel] It is unknown which hominid species first used fire, as both *Australopithecus* and an early species of *Homo* were present at the sites.
[src:fuel/fuel] As a fuel, wood has remained in use up until the present day, although it has been superseded for many purposes by other sources.
[src:fuel/fuel] Wood has an energy density of 10–20 MJ/kg.
[src:fuel/fuel] Recently biofuels have been developed for use in automotive transport (for example bioethanol and biodiesel), but there is widespread public debate about how carbon neutral these fuels are.
[src:fuel/fuel] Fossil fuels are hydrocarbons, primarily coal and petroleum (liquid petroleum or natural gas), formed from the fossilized remains of ancient plants and animals by exposure to high heat and pressure in the absence of oxygen in the Earth's crust over hundreds of millions of years.
[src:fuel/fuel] Commonly, the term fossil fuel also includes hydrocarbon-containing natural resources that are not derived entirely from biological sources, such as tar sands.
[src:fuel/fuel] These latter sources are properly known as *mineral fuels*.
[src:fuel/fuel] Fossil fuels contain high percentages of carbon and include coal, petroleum, and natural gas.
[src:fuel/fuel] They range from volatile materials with low carbon:hydrogen ratios like methane, to liquid petroleum to nonvolatile materials composed of almost pure carbon, like anthracite coal.
[src:fuel/fuel] Methane can be found in hydrocarbon fields, alone, associated with oil, or in the form of methane clathrates.
[src:fuel/fuel] Fossil fuels formed from the fossilized remains of dead plants by exposure to heat and pressure in the Earth's crust over millions of years.
[src:fuel/fuel] This biogenic theory was first introduced by German scholar Georg Agricola in 1556 and later by Mikhail Lomonosov in the 18th century.
[src:fuel/fuel] It was estimated by the Energy Information Administration that in 2007 primary sources of energy consisted of petroleum 36.0%, coal 27.4%, natural gas 23.0%, amounting to an 86.4% share for fossil fuels in primary energy consumption in the world.
[src:fuel/fuel] Non-fossil sources in 2006 included hydroelectric 6.3%, nuclear 8.5%, and others (geothermal, solar, tidal, wind, wood, waste) amounting to 0.9%.
[src:fuel/fuel] World energy consumption was growing about 2.3% per year.
[src:fuel/fuel] Fossil fuels are non-renewable resources because they take millions of years to form, and reserves are being depleted much faster than new ones are being made.
[src:fuel/fuel] So we must conserve these fuels and use them judiciously.
[src:fuel/fuel] The production and use of fossil fuels raise environmental concerns.
[src:fuel/fuel] A global movement toward the generation of renewable energy is therefore under way to help meet increased energy needs.
[src:fuel/fuel] Carbon dioxide is one of the greenhouse gases that enhances radiative forcing and contributes to global warming, causing the average surface temperature of the Earth to rise in response, which the vast majority of climate scientists agree will cause major adverse effects.
[src:fuel/fuel] The International Energy Agency (IEA) predicts that fossil fuel prices will decline, with oil stabilizing around $75 to $80 per barrel as electric vehicle adoption surges and renewable energy expands.
[src:fuel/fuel] Additionally, the IEA anticipates a notable increase in liquefied natural gas capacity, enhancing Europe's energy diversification.
[src:fuel/fuel] The amount of energy from different types of fuel depends on the stoichiometric ratio, the chemically correct air and fuel ratio to ensure complete combustion of fuel, and its specific energy, the energy per unit mass.
[src:fuel/fuel] Nuclear fuel is any material that is consumed to derive nuclear energy.
[src:fuel/fuel] In theory, a wide variety of substances could be a nuclear fuel, as they can be made to release nuclear energy under the right conditions.
[src:fuel/fuel] However, the materials commonly referred to as nuclear fuels are those that will produce energy without being placed under extreme duress.
[src:fuel/fuel] Nuclear fuel can be "burned" by nuclear fission (splitting nuclei apart) or fusion (combining nuclei together) to derive nuclear energy.
[src:fuel/fuel] "Nuclear fuel" can refer to the fuel itself, or to physical objects (for example bundles composed of **fuel rods**) composed of the fuel material, mixed with structural, neutron moderating, or neutron-reflecting materials.
[src:fuel/fuel] Nuclear fuel has the highest energy density of all practical fuel sources.
[src:fuel/fuel] When some of these fuels are struck by neutrons, they are in turn capable of emitting neutrons when they break apart.
[src:fuel/fuel] This makes possible a self-sustaining chain reaction that releases energy at a controlled rate in a nuclear reactor, or at a very rapid uncontrolled rate in a nuclear weapon.
[src:fuel/fuel] The most common fissile nuclear fuels are uranium-235 (235U) and plutonium-239 (239Pu).
[src:fuel/fuel] The actions of mining, refining, purifying, using, and ultimately disposing of nuclear fuel together make up the nuclear fuel cycle.
[src:fuel/fuel] Not all types of nuclear fuels create energy from nuclear fission.
[src:fuel/fuel] Plutonium-238 and some other elements are used to produce small amounts of nuclear energy by radioactive decay in radioisotope thermoelectric generators and other types of atomic batteries.
[src:fuel/fuel] In contrast to fission, some light nuclides such as tritium (3H) can be used as fuel for nuclear fusion.
[src:fuel/fuel] This involves two or more nuclei combining into larger nuclei.
[src:fuel/fuel] Fuels that produce energy by this method are currently not utilized by humans, but they are the main source of fuel for stars.
[src:fuel/fuel] Fusion fuels are light elements such as hydrogen whose nucleii will combine easily.
[src:fuel/fuel] Energy is required to start fusion by raising the temperature so high that nuclei can collide together with enough energy that they stick together before repelling due to electric charge.
[src:fuel/fuel] This process is called fusion and it can give out energy.
[src:fuel/fuel] In stars that undergo nuclear fusion, fuel consists of atomic nuclei that can release energy by the absorption of a proton or neutron.
[src:fuel/fuel] In most stars the fuel is provided by hydrogen, which can combine to form helium through the proton-proton chain reaction or by the CNO cycle.
[src:fuel/fuel] When the hydrogen fuel is exhausted, nuclear fusion can continue with progressively heavier elements, although the net energy released is lower because of the smaller difference in nuclear binding energy.
[src:fuel/fuel] Once iron-56 or nickel-56 nuclei are produced, no further energy can be obtained by nuclear fusion as these have the highest nuclear binding energies.
[src:fuel/fuel] Any nucleii heavier than 56Fe and 56Ni would thus absorb energy instead of giving it off when fused.
[src:fuel/fuel] Therefore, fusion stops and the star dies.
[src:fuel/fuel] In attempts by humans, fusion is only carried out with hydrogen (2H (deuterium) or 3H (tritium)) to form helium-4 as this reaction gives out the most net energy.
[src:fuel/fuel] Electric confinement (ITER), inertial confinement (heating by laser) and heating by strong electric currents are the popular methods.
[src:fuel/fuel] Most transportation fuels are liquids, because vehicles usually require high energy density.
[src:fuel/fuel] This occurs naturally in liquids and solids.
[src:fuel/fuel] High energy density can also be provided by an internal combustion engine.
[src:fuel/fuel] These engines require clean-burning fuels.
[src:fuel/fuel] The fuels that are easiest to burn cleanly are typically liquids and gases.
[src:fuel/fuel] Thus, liquids meet the requirements of being both energy-dense and clean-burning.
[src:fuel/fuel] In addition, liquids (and gases) can be pumped, which means handling is easily mechanized, and thus less laborious.
[src:fuel/fuel] As there is a general movement towards a low carbon economy, the use of liquid fuels such as hydrocarbons is coming under scrutiny.
